/*

WELCOME TO THE I18N READ ME!

--SECTION 0: What the HECK is i18n?--
        Modding Wiki Page:  https://stardewmodding.wiki.gg/wiki/Tutorial:_How_to_make_your_mod_compatible_with_other_languages

        i18n, which stands for internationalization, is the method that content patcher uses to allow for translations into other languages. 
            Essentially it takes any display text inside your mod and puts it somewhere else that is easier for translators to access.
            Otherwise, they would need to reupload your entire mod, and no one really wants that.
            It has quite a few other perks, such as injecting specific tokens into a key to make multiple at once, reducing the amount of patches you need.
            That's fairly advanced though, so don't worry about that for now. The only instance of it in this template is festival dialogue located in Data/Festivals.json

--SECTION 1: Do I haaaave to?--
        Short answer: 
            No.
        Long answer: 
            No, but you absolutely should from the start of your mod or you will regret it if/when you choose to do it to make your mod translatable. 
            You also miss out on a lot of advanced tricks that do Super Cool Stuff and make your life easier when you get more comfortable with Content Patcher.
            There are tools to make i18n a more automated process, such as: https://nom0ri.github.io/sdv-i18nifier-app/


--SECTION 2: How the sausage gets made.--
        Ready to try out i18n?
        
            No?

                Too bad, here comes the explanation!

        i18n seems intimidating at first, but it's fairy straight forward once you get used to it. 
            First, i18n typically only works in locations with display text. So think item names, location names, descriptions, dialogue...
            i18n will inject your desired text into a field from another file in a mad-libs sort of way. This means yes, you can use the same key in multiple locations if text repeats.
            
        Lets use Data/Characters/Dialogue as an example.
            Before i18n, you'll start with a key that looks like this:
            
                Data/Dialogue.json -> 
                                 Code->
                                   "Introduction": "Hi, this is me!"

            Great, they're talking! But that dialogue is hardcoded into your mod. 
            This means translators would need to reupload your mod or preform invasive patches to change this text.
            So, this is where i18n keys come in...
            You'll open an i18n json and create a new key and fill in the specified text. THIS CAN BE NAMED ANYTHING! (usually) 

                i18n ->
                    Default ->
                        Dialogue.json ->
                            "i18nKeyHere": "Your dialogue here."
                            "Dialogue.Introduction": "Hi, this is me!" (For the previous example)

        So head back to "Introduction" in Dialogue.json. and delete the display text like so:

            "Introduction": "" 

        Now we'll swap out the text for the i18n key. These keys typically look like this: {{i18n: KeyHere}}.

            "Introduction": "{{i18n: Dialogue.Introduction}}" 

        Then that's it, you're done. Dialogue will be printed in the game normally, but also be fully translatable.
    

--SECTION 3: OH GOD. WHAT DO I NAME MY KEYS?!--
        Don't overthink it! With a few exceptions, i18n keys can be named anything you want.
        This allows you to format your keys in a way that works best for you.
            Examples: Youri18nKey, Your_i18n_Key, Your.i18n.Key, Your.i18n_Key

        A couple of things require a specific name for an i18n key
           Generic Mod Config Config i81n: https://github.com/Pathoschild/StardewMods/blob/develop/ContentPatcher/docs/author-guide/config.md
           Tokens that have tokens injected into them: See Data/Festivals.json Dialogue patch and i18n/Default/Festival.json
           Other things that I'm likely not aware of
        
--SECTION 4: How do I sort my files?--
        i18n files are fairly straight forward. You can either have a single default.json or a Default folder with multiple smaller json files.
            Single default.json - Good for tiny mods that don't need a lot of organization
            Multiple .json files - Good for a mod with many moving parts, like an NPC or an expansion. These files can be named anything.

        These will be your potential file structures:
            i18n
                -> Default.json

            i18n
                -> Default
                    -> Config.json
                    -> Dialogue.json
                    -> Events.json
                    -> ...

--SECTION 5: Anything else I should know?--
        i18n files can use any in-game commands for dialogue and such, but it CANNOT use Content Patcher features.

            This includes, but is not limited to:
                * Loading files
                * Including files
                * Editing files
                * Text Operations
                * Tokens
            
            There are some work around for using tokens in i18n, though this is fairly advanced. 
            You should get comfortable with basic Content Patcher modding before learning these methods:
                Localized Text: https://stardewvalleywiki.com/Modding:Tokenizable_strings 
                    * Preferred
                    * Cleaner 
                    * Typically requires loading a new internal file for your strings

                Pass-in Tokens:  https://github.com/Pathoschild/StardewMods/blob/develop/ContentPatcher/docs/author-guide/translations.md#can-i-use-content-patcher-tokens-in-i18n-files
                    * Less ideal
                    * Messier
                    * Doesn't require loading a new internal file

*/
}